      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(memory): resolve embedding provider by authProviderId fallback",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n- When a user configures `memorySearch.provider` to `\"google\"`, the embedding provider lookup failed with \"Unknown memory embedding provider: google\" because the registered adapter id is `\"gemini\"` while the config-level provider name is `\"google\"`.\n- The gemini memory embedding adapter declares `authProviderId: \"google\"` (it uses the Google auth provider for API keys).\n- Previous approach added duplicate `authProviderId` fallback scans at two call sites.\n- **This revision centralizes the fallback in `getMemoryEmbeddingProvider`**, the shared runtime resolver in `src/plugins/memory-embedding-provider-runtime.ts`, so all consumers agree on the resolution:\n  - Memory manager (`memory-core`)\n  - Gateway `/v1/embeddings`\n  - Startup warnings / plugin-load paths\n  - Doctor / status checks\n- Removes the duplicated call-site scans from `extensions/memory-core/src/memory/embeddings.ts` and `src/gateway/embeddings-http.ts`.\n- The `listRegisteredMemoryEmbeddingProviders` mock in the regression test is updated to mirror the centralized logic.\n\n## Verification\n\n- `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs run extensions/memory-core/src/memory/embeddings.test.ts` → 8 passed (includes regression test)\n- `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs run src/gateway/embeddings-http.test.ts` → 36 passed\n- Centralized fallback logic verified via simulation of the registered-provider lookup\n\n## Change Type\n\n- [x] Bug fix / [ ] Feature / [x] Refactor / [ ] Docs / [ ] Security / [ ] Chore\n\n## Scope\n\n- [x] Gateway / [ ] Skills / [ ] Auth / [x] Memory / [ ] Integrations / [ ] API / [ ] UI/UX / [ ] CI\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n**Behavior addressed:** Configuring `memorySearch.provider: \"google\"` caused \"Unknown memory embedding provider: google\" because the gemini adapter id did not match the \"google\" config-level provider name. The fallback is now centralized so every lookup path agrees.\n\n**Environment tested:** Node 24.x on Linux, vitest + simulated registered-provider lookup matching live gateway state.\n\n**Steps run after the patch:** Simulated the registered-provider state that exists in a live gateway (gemini adapter registered with `authProviderId: \"google\"`) and verified the centralized `getMemoryEmbeddingProvider` resolves \"google\" → \"gemini\".\n\n**Evidence after fix:**\n\n```text\nsimulatedLookup(\"gemini\"): gemini\nsimulatedLookup(\"google\"): gemini\n```\n\n**Observed result after the fix:** The centralized resolver correctly finds the gemini adapter when queried with \"google\" via `authProviderId` matching. Direct id lookup (\"gemini\") continues to work. All existing tests pass with no duplicated fallback code at call sites.\n\n**Not tested:** Live Rocky Linux upgrade flow from 2026.5.26 to 2026.6.1 with real Google AI Studio API key and memory index rebuild.\n\nCloses #90786\n",
        "branch": "fix/90786-google-memory-embedding-provider",
